he Function of Dreams in Middle High German Narrative Literature -- tMonstra nobiscum: Medieval and Early Modern Teratology and the Confluence of Imaginatio and Scientia -- tJews and Anti-Jewish Fantasies in Christian Imagination in the Middle Ages -- tThe Life of Christ in Medieval Bestiaries: Imagining the Griffin, Lion, Unicorn, Pelican, and Phoenix -- tMonsters, Grotesques, and Other Marvels in the Later Medieval Imagination -- tFantastic Places, Objects, and Creatures in Fourteenth-Century Czech-Language Literature: Imagination During the Reign of the Luxembourg Dynasty -- tThe Mermaid of Edam and the Emergence of Dutch National Identity -- tDream and Prophetic Projection in Andreas Gryphius’s Historical Tragedies: Traces of the Symbol -- tThe Shadow of the Knight: Phantom Fears and their Distortions of Reality in Baroque Spanish Theater -- tFantasy, Imagination, and Vision in Thomas Vaughan’s Lumen de Lumine -- tBiographies of the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe notions of other peoples, cultures, and natural conditions have always been determined by the epistemology of imagination and fantasy, providing much freedom and creativity, and yet have also created much fear, anxiety, and horror. In this regard, the pre-modern world demonstrates striking parallels with our own insofar as the projections of alterity might be different by degrees, but they are fundamentally the same by content. Dreams, illusions, projections, concepts, hopes, utopias/dystopias, desires, and emotional attachments are as specific and impactful as the physical environment. This volume thus sheds important light on the various lenses used by people in the Middle Ages and the early modern age as to how they came to terms with their perceptions, images, and notions. Previous scholarship focused heavily on the history of mentality and history of emotions, whereas here the history of pre-modern imagination, and fantasy assumes center position. Imaginary things are taken seriously because medieval and early modern writers and artists clearly reveal their great significance in their works and their daily lives. This approach facilitates a new deep-structure analysis of pre-modern culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aFantasyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aImaginationxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 4aFantasie. 4aFrühe Neuzeit. 4aImagination. 4aMittelalter. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aImagination.  afantasy.  amedieval and early modern concepts.1 aAbed, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeal, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenati, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennett, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristoph, Siegfried, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCurrie, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFajardo-Acosta, Fidel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerland, Emmy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHrbek, Filip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJiménez, Luis Isidro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandau Ames, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoffitt Peacock, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPigg, Daniel F., econt